Dear Palos 118 Families,

We continue to monitor all recommendations for public schools from the Illinois Department of Public Health (IDPH), the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) and Illinois State Board of Education (ISBE) regarding the COVID-19 virus. I am meeting with district administrators this morning to review all updated recommendations. Communication regarding additional preventative measures to be taken by the school district will be shared later today.

Thank you for your cooperation as we continue to respond to this public health concern.

Sincerely,
Dr. Anthony M. Scarsella
Superintendent of Schools

post_text:
This morning, the Cook County Sheriff’s Department performed a canine sweep of Palos South Middle School at the request of school administrators. During the sweep, a small amount of cannabis was discovered. School administrators and the Cook County Sheriff’s Department are working with the students and families involved. At no time was there a threat to student safety.

Student safety remains our top priority. We ask parents to please speak with your children about the potential negative consequences resulting from these types of incidents.

Sincerely,

Mr. Wrzesinski & Ms. Doornbos
Palos South Middle School

post_text:
Dear Parents,

This morning, students reported a suspicious odor at Palos South Middle School. As a precaution, a canine unit from the Cook County Sheriff’s Office performed a building sweep. During the sweep, students were held in their classrooms as they normally would when the school performs a hold and secure. Please be advised that there is no threat to student safety. We will provide an update should additional information become available.

post_text:
A Message from Dr. Scarsella:

Good afternoon,

This morning we received a report of suspicious activity involving a cream colored SUV at a bus stop at 130th Street and 86th Avenue that occurred yesterday afternoon. Students at the stop reported the possibility of the driver taking pictures of them. Parents reported the incident to the Cook County Sheriff's Department and officers are investigating. We have no additional details from the Sheriff at this time. Additional patrols have been added to the area as a precaution.

Now that school has started, I am asking our entire school community to be vigilant of suspicious activity at bus stops and immediately report any suspicious activity to local police and your child's school. Student safety remains our top priority and I thank you in advance for working with us to ensure our students remain safe traveling to and from school this school year.

Thank you,

Dr. Anthony Scarsella
Superintendent of Schools

post_text: Wondering how your student might perform on the PSAT 8/9 when they reach 8th grade? Knowing how they perform on the Illinois Assessment of Readiness (IAR) is a good indication. Students who approach, meet, or exceed on the IAR are highly likely to be on grade level in 9th grade. The more we all know about our students’ performance, the better we can prepare them for their future.
text: Wondering how your student might perform on the PSAT 8/9 when they reach 8th grade? Knowing how they perform on the Illinois Assessment of Readiness (IAR) is a good indication. Students who approach, meet, or exceed on the IAR are highly likely to be on grade level in 9th grade. The more we all know about our students’ performance, the better we can prepare them for their future.

post_text: Did you know the Illinois Assessment of Readiness measures both grade level proficiency and student growth with a much greater emphasis on student growth? This is an exciting change long advocated by Illinois educators. See what ISBE has to say about other improvements to the state’s assessment system.
